("**Explaining placeholder name origins**"
 "“John Doe” (and its partner “Richard Roe”) comes out of **English common-law procedure**, especially **ejectment** (real-property) lawsuits from roughly the **16th–18th centuries**.\n\n### Origin in English legal fictions\nTo get land-title disputes into a court form that was procedurally convenient, lawyers used a *standardized fiction*: they alleged that a fictional person had been leased the land and then wrongfully “ejected.” The case would be styled as if:\n\n- **John Doe** = the fictitious tenant/claimant\n- **Richard Roe** = the fictitious ejector/defendant\n\nThese names became conventional placeholders and were printed in forms and reported cases, so “John Doe” stuck as a general “unknown/stand-in person” name.\n\n### Where “Jane Doe” comes from\n“Jane Doe” is essentially the **later, female counterpart** formed by analogy (and widely used in the U.S. for unknown women, unidentified bodies, etc.). Historically the classic paired name in the old English procedure was **Richard Roe**, not Jane.\n\n### Why “Doe”?\n“Doe” was chosen because it was:\n- a **real, ordinary English surname** (short, common enough, unremarkable), suitable for a generic person;\n- already in circulation in legal and folk placeholder naming traditions (lawyers also used other generic names like “John a Nokes and John a Stiles,” etc.).\n\nThe fact that *doe* also means a **female deer** is mostly incidental; the legal use is about the surname being a convenient, generic stand-in.")
